quote: Unfortunately I dont see what most see in 1917. Respectively, I hardly feel anything except some respect for the technical achievements. But that alone isnt enough - it actually slightly damages the film overall.
critic.name: Jimmy Cage
publication.name: Jimmy Cage Movie Reviews (YouTube)

quote: The film's formal indulgences distract from its dramatic potential.
critic.name: Brian Eggert
publication.name: Deep Focus Review

quote: What makes it so special is the balance between artistry and realism. Mendes reaches down into the mud and finds something beautiful.
critic.name: James Luxford
publication.name: City AM

quote: 1917 is a technical masterpiece that comes together with genuine powerful emotion to become a captivating work of art.
critic.name: Carson Timar
publication.name: Filmotomy

quote: We should be drawn into the personal story--director Sam Mendes loosely based the movie on his grandfather Alfred's wartime experiences--but instead, we're watching all the smoke and mirrors. It's sound and fury that could signify so much more.
critic.name: Salome Gonstad
publication.name: Comic Years

quote: What could have been a gimmick in the service of a weaker narrative becomes a masterstroke here, basically denying us any let-off from the tension of what is happening on the screen.
critic.name: Graeme Tuckett
publication.name: Stuff.co.nz

quote: It is a must-see.
critic.name: Lonita Cook
publication.name: KCTV5 News at 9

quote: The gimmicky side of [its single take] fades juxtaposed to the perspective it offers.
critic.name: Milana Vujkov
publication.name: Lola On Film

quote: In addition to Deakins, production designer Dennis Gassner and composer Thomas Newman also add layers of bravura artistry to create an experience that will leave you breathless, heart pounding and absolutely emotionally wrecked by the end.
critic.name: Catherine Springer
publication.name: CathsFilmForum.com

quote: Mendes creates one of the best films released in 2019.
critic.name: Robin Holabird
publication.name: KUNR (Reno, NV)

quote: Forget gushing quotes and star ratings. Probably the most effective way to advertise this movie is to strap heart rate monitors on viewers and put the results on the poster.
critic.name: Richard Trenholm
publication.name: CNET

quote: The filmmakers have taken a simple premise and gone with a "less is more" tactic. This allows for more focus on a beautifully shot film, and highlights the actors who give their all emotionally and physically.
critic.name: Susan Kamyab
publication.name: This Chix Flix

quote: 1917 can safely be added to the list of movies that have expanded and enhanced our understanding of how truly brutal war can be.
critic.name: Alex Bentley
publication.name: CultureMap

quote: 1917, under the talented hands of Sam Mendes, is one of the best war movies ever made and one of the best of 2019.
critic.name: Nicole Ackman
publication.name: In Their Own League

quote: This is a contemplative story of a mission and the men who sacrifice their own safety for the greater good. It highlights the ever-present danger of attack but it is the character's emotional journey that makes for a compelling story.
critic.name: Richard Crouse
publication.name: Richard Crouse

quote: A measured compromise of its emotional quotient to create a visual feast, [1917] is undoubtedly impressive while remaining remote.
critic.name: Jeffrey Zhang
publication.name: Strange Harbors

quote: Sam Mende's quiet WWI epic 1917 is a cinematic masterpiece, a near perfect war film that appeals to even those of us who don't particularly enjoy war movies ... To put it even simpler, this film is bananas.
critic.name: Candice McMillan
publication.name: KOMO News (Seattle)

quote: ... [C]heck[s] the box that indicates war is, indeed, hell. But this is not the same as actually taking that truth seriously.
critic.name: Fletcher Powell
publication.name: KMUW - Wichita Public Radio

quote: Despite the intermittent cinematographic interruptions to the nerve-wracking immersion in WWI chaos, the movie remains unwaveringly tense.
critic.name: Mike Massie
publication.name: Gone With The Twins

quote: Its visual artistry places it among the best historical war films of the past decade or two.
critic.name: John Serba
publication.name: Decider

quote: The film's final hour loses steam and is beset by more than a few narrative lapses it ultimately can't overcome. Still, this is a worthwhile epic best seen on the big screen.
critic.name: Charles Koplinski
publication.name: Reel Talk with Chuck and Pam

quote: Although it hardly goes beyond being technically bold, it still is quite admirable in its ambition.
critic.name: Matthew St. Clair
publication.name: Cinema Sentries

quote: War is hell and Sam Mendes's hell is quiet and real and intimate and suspenseful and you feel it in your bones long after you leave the theatre.
critic.name: Richard Propes
publication.name: TheIndependentCritic.com

quote: At this current level of Hollywood production, expressionistic British militarism is all the same to me and it's worn me out...
critic.name: A.S. Hamrah
publication.name: The Baffler

quote: 1917 looks and feels like a 1st person shooter game, and every scene is just preparation to react to what happens in the next scene.
critic.name: MontiLee Stormer
publication.name: MovieReelist.com

quote: A dazzling experience that feels both authentic and thrillingly cinematic.
critic.name: Andrew Gaudion
publication.name: THN

quote: When the soldiers struggle through near-darkness in a collapsing tunnel, we suffocate with them. When a plane plunges from the sky towards them, it's an almighty effort not to leap from your seat.
critic.name: Stephen A. Russell
publication.name: The New Daily (Australia)

quote: A technological step forward, several ideological and artistic steps back...
critic.name: Joanne Laurier
publication.name: World Socialist Web Site

quote: The narrative may be simple, but the visual approach taken by the film is astonishingly complex.
critic.name: Scott Phillips
publication.name: The Screen Scene

quote: The single take is no gimmick, but a way of forcing you to sit through every minute of wartime, with all of its horror and false hope.
critic.name: James Hanton
publication.name: Outtake Mag

quote: Although the word is thrown around a lot, I would certainly consider 1917 to be a masterpiece in every sense of the word.
critic.name: Lucy Buglass
publication.name: Lucy Goes to Hollywood

quote: While in some ways 1917 speaks the visual language of a current-day shooter video game, the performances elevate the film to almost operatic drama
critic.name: Bill Newcott
publication.name: The Saturday Evening Post

quote: From Alfred Hitchcock's "Rope" to Alejandro Iñárritu's "Birdman," only a rare few have ever dared to shoot a film that appears to unfold in one single take. Now imagine pulling it off in a war movie with timed explosions all around the set.
critic.name: Jason Fraley
publication.name: WTOP (Washington, D.C.)

quote: Although 1917 will not change your life, there's no doubt it's an audiovisual spectacle of the highest order. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Ricardo Gallegos
publication.name: Pólvora

quote: This is a suspenseful, character driven war drama that only intensifies the further along it goes.
critic.name: Allen Almachar
publication.name: The MacGuffin

quote: As a formal exercise, it's impossible not to admire. But when it comes to that crucial emotional connection, it left me feeling stranded in no man's land.
critic.name: Adam Lubitow
publication.name: Rochester City Newspaper

quote: A cinematic experience that shakes my sensations at the time it moves me to the hell of a war that is constantly threatened by light and darkness. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Yasser Medina
publication.name: Cinemaficionados

quote: [1917 has] a rather simple plot for what turns out to be one of those rare films that can be truly worthy of the title Cinematic Experience.
critic.name: Damond Fudge
publication.name: KCCI (Des Moines, IA)

quote: It's safe to say that 1917 is a phenomenal technical display of a captivating war-time drama. It's visually enthralling, and the film is sure to keep you engaged all the way through.
critic.name: Emmanuel Noisette
publication.name: The Movie Blog

quote: Mendes has produced a thrillingly immersive movie... We might be even more involved in the soldiers' fates were we not also boggling over the staggering technical feats that went into the film's making.
critic.name: Jason Best
publication.name: Marie Claire

quote: 1917 ignores larger questions about war for something more personal and humanistic and George MacKay's excellent performance is key to this.
critic.name: Andrew Kendall
publication.name: Stabroek News

quote: A brutal, tense and unforgiving film that achieves the highs in technicality by balancing it with a triumphant look at the bravery on the war-front.
critic.name: Shikhar Verma
publication.name: High on Films

quote: A tribute to, and reminder of, those brave men, young and old, who fought on the front lines in a vicious war.
critic.name: Matthew Pejkovic
publication.name: Matt's Movie Reviews

quote: One word: immersive. That's pretty much sums up Sam Mendes' highly-ambitious World War I epic, "1917".
critic.name: Casey Chong
publication.name: Casey's Movie Mania

quote: 1917 is one of the best war films I have ever seen. Epic from beginning to end, it truly captures the horrors of trench warfare.
critic.name: Tessa Smith
publication.name: Mama's Geeky

quote: A journey worth taking. Mendes keeps his film brilliantly paced throughout.
critic.name: Paul Chambers
publication.name: Movie Chambers

quote: Sam Mendes' 1917 is a remarkable technical achievement, utilizing brilliant direction, cinematography, editing, visual effects, production design, and sound design, to tell a spellbinding tale that easily ranks as one of the very best films of 2019.
critic.name: Jeff Beck
publication.name: The Blu Spot

quote: 1917 isn't just a nail-biting war movie, it's a vital and timeless account of heroism and a depiction of humanity at its most desperate yet hopeful. We need stories like this one, especially now.
critic.name: Frank J. Avella
publication.name: Edge Media Network

quote: 'Arthouse World War I mood-piece as live-action videogame Let's Play' isn't exactly a populous subgenre; though one has to assume 'What if Ernest Hemmingway had made Hardcore Henry?' is a pitch that would raise at least a few eyebrows.
critic.name: Bob Chipman
publication.name: Escapist Magazine

quote: The beautiful cinematography cannot make up for the weak screenplay and performances that pale in comparison to Roger Deakins' imagery.
critic.name: Julia Swift
publication.name: My Champlain Valley

quote: It is a brilliant appropriation of the pains and aches of war for the purpose of creating something that is pure cinema.
critic.name: Oggs Cruz
publication.name: Rappler

quote: A cinematic experience on war, tension, and the boundaries of drama within a realistic setting of desperation. [Full review in Spanish].
critic.name: Federico Furzan
publication.name: Cinelipsis

quote: Filmmaker Mendes, working from a script written with Krysty Wilson-Cairns, does a superb job of immediately drawing the viewer into the stylish proceedings...
critic.name: David Nusair
publication.name: Reel Film Reviews

quote: An overwhelming accomplishment in filmmaking, 1917 might be more "experience" than "film" but oh, what an experience it is nonetheless.
critic.name: Brian Gill
publication.name: Mad About Movies Podcast

quote: It's hard to be immersive when you're constantly calling attention to yourself, and it's impossible when your camera is more the protagonist of your film than your characters.
critic.name: Isaac Feldberg
publication.name: Fortune

quote: An experiment that worked.
critic.name: Bob Grimm
publication.name: Reno News and Review

quote: As a whole, the film fails cinematically even if some scenes are effective.
critic.name: Sr. Rose Pacatte
publication.name: Sister Rose at the Movies

quote: A 'don't-miss' masterpiece.
critic.name: Linda Cook
publication.name: Quad City Times (Davenport, IA)

quote: However technically impressive it is, "1917," the movie, is just as pointless.
critic.name: Loren King
publication.name: Newport This Week (RI)

quote: Although the story's engagement levels can dip between set pieces, the skill of Mendes' collaborators elevates 1917 to something a little more than the marketing hooks would imply, even if technical prowess still dominates the emotions of the characters.
critic.name: Jim Ross
publication.name: TAKE ONE Magazine

quote: One of the most technically proficient, emotionally compelling, and jaw-dropping goliaths of a war film that I've ever seen.
critic.name: Morgan Rojas
publication.name: Cinemacy

quote: Excellent, but more of a technical spectacle than a compelling movie...cinematography is stunning...
critic.name: Shawn Edwards
publication.name: Fox 4 Kansas City

quote: 1917 is as much of an endurance test in the cinema as it seemingly was on the other side of the camera, and it's one that lands with a grotesque, powerful punch.
critic.name: Tom Beasley
publication.name: Flickering Myth

quote: a gripping, harrowing portrait of war that is made all the more compelling by its tight narrative and temporal focus
critic.name: James Kendrick
publication.name: Q Network Film Desk

quote: Mendes and Co. make it all seem fresh and vital again. This is a a movie filled with gorgeous and grotesque imagery...
critic.name: Stephen Rebello
publication.name: Playboy Online

quote: Sam Mendes' film makes incremental updates to the war movie genre...
critic.name: Li Lai
publication.name: Mediaversity Reviews

quote: The film grabs you from the beginning moments and never really lets you go. It is so realistic that your stomach is in knots wishing the best for the two young soldiers.
critic.name: Carey-Ann Pawsey
publication.name: Orca Sound

quote: One of the most amazing productions I've ever seen. The cinemaphotography, with its opening super-long tracking shot...(what did we do before Steadicams?)
critic.name: Diane Pershing
publication.name: Malibu Times

quote: 1917 is a great film. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Hugo Hernández Valdivia
publication.name: Cinexcepción

quote: It's worth seeing even though one resents the fact that the visual scheme was understood as an end goal in itself. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: William Venegas
publication.name: La Nación (Costa Rica)

quote: An audiovisual artwork about the war. The art of the war as Sun Tzu says or the absurd of the war as Sam Mendes Says. Photographically a must [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Guillem Martinez Oya
publication.name: Cinematismo

quote: The film is beautifully shot and is exceedingly effective on a visceral level, showing the horrors of war and the bravery that occurs.
critic.name: Nick Boyd
publication.name: Battle Royale With Cheese

quote: In a word, it's a masterpiece.
critic.name: Josh Davis
publication.name: Pop Culture Leftovers

quote: The end result is poignant, affecting, and heart-breaking; a film that can stand shoulder to shoulder with the best war movies while serving as a timely reminder of the horrific loss and utter devastation left behind by conflict.
critic.name: Sameen Amer
publication.name: The News International (Pakistan)

quote: Qualms aside, this is still a powerful film that makes effective use of visuals, sound and music.
critic.name: Matthew Toomey
publication.name: ABC Radio (Australia)

quote: There are some plot distentions, but the film also piles up moments of true fascination... By the end, you'll feel as exhausted as the messenger.
critic.name: Filipe Freitas
publication.name: Always Good Movies

quote: A very conservative war film employing a single-take strategy which, ironically, neuters it of any authenticity. It feels stage-managed, curated and airbrushed.
critic.name: PJ Nabarro
publication.name: Patrick Nabarro

quote: A movie that vibrates, spectacular and febrile. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Luis Martínez
publication.name: El Mundo (Spain)

quote: Emotional and poetic in its spectacular mixture of noise, chaos and almost abstract calm. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Marcos Gandía
publication.name: Sensacine

quote: Finding the point in things that seem pointless.
critic.name: Damian Levy
publication.name: Jamaica Gleaner

quote: If the technique elevates a simple story to an intense and immersive 'tour de force', the actors raise it in spirit and dignity. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Benjamín Harguindey
publication.name: EscribiendoCine

quote: As a work of visual spectacle,1917 is an exceptional piece of work: in turns dramatic, thrilling, and occasionally trascendent.
critic.name: Grant Watson
publication.name: Fiction Machine

quote: Much has been said and written about the cinematographic marvel that is 1917... But Sam Mendes movie is much more than that[Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Pablo O. Scholz
publication.name: Clarín

quote: A physical and psychic exploration... of the devastating consequences of the First World War. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Diego Batlle
publication.name: La Nación (Argentina)

quote: 1917 reminds us how lucky we are to be able to see certain stories accompanied by the complicity and darkness of a movie theater. [Full review in spanish]
critic.name: Arturo Magaña
publication.name: Cine Premiere

quote: A fascinatingly nuanced form of environmental and character evolution.
critic.name: Sean O'Rourke
publication.name: Film Ireland Magazine

quote: As a genre piece, I think it's really interesting -- well made and immersive. But as a kind of emotional movie that really pulled me in, I don't know if it did that.
critic.name: Simran Hans
publication.name: Monocle

quote: 1917 is not just an incredible film because it's about war, but because it is a film about humanity.
critic.name: Jessica Mason
publication.name: The Mary Sue

quote: In a purely technical sense, 1917 achieves exactly what it sets out to do. But in the process, it loses the relationship between images and cinema's ability to create meaning beneath the surface.
critic.name: Siddhant Adlakha
publication.name: Polygon

quote: It's a technically impressive movie, but also an empty and trivial one. [Full review in Portuguese]
critic.name: Pablo Villaça
publication.name: Cinema em Cena

quote: 1917 is tense, captivating, meticulous, horrifying and stirring.
critic.name: Neil Soans
publication.name: The Times of India

quote: A masterclass in suspense-building from beginning to end...
critic.name: Rahul Desai
publication.name: Film Companion

quote: This movie deserves to be watched in a cinema hall...choreography the likes of which I haven't seen, refusing to let you even breathe...
critic.name: Sucharita Tyagi
publication.name: Film Companion

quote: With a far more assured touch and with unrivalled intensity, Mendes gives us a film that encapsulates the madness and futility of war from way back in the last millennium right down to this day and age.
critic.name: Rashid Irani
publication.name: Scroll.in

quote: Sam Mendes's Oscar-nominated film may be talked about for its beautiful direction and cinematography, but it should be long remembered for George MacKay's performance.
critic.name: Michael Baumann
publication.name: The Ringer

quote: It proves that its long takes, instead of being a way of making things more difficult or 'artistic', are a vital component for this particular story. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Sebastian Zavala Kahn
publication.name: Me gusta el cine

quote: An emotional and artistic masterclass.
critic.name: Roe McDermott
publication.name: Hot Press

quote: 1917 has established itself as one of the best war films of all time. The incredible cinematography by Deakins & strong performance by George MacKay combine to create a beautiful experience.
critic.name: Sheraz Farooqi
publication.name: CinemaDebate

quote: The film is pure spectacle and nothing more. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Israel Acosta Aroche
publication.name: Konexión

quote: The fresh thing about this one is its set up to look like one continuous tracking shot. The whole movie, the entire movie looks like it's just one continuous shot, which is pretty damn amazing.
critic.name: Tony Baker
publication.name: Tony Baker Comedy

quote: Everything is monumental, as if the physical and moral devastation of the great war of 14-18 had to be seen through the distorting prism of the representation that Hollywood has provided for years. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Carlos Bonfil
publication.name: La Jornada

quote: It does not bother anyone. Its speech is noble. And it is impeccably filmed. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Leonardo Garcia Tsao
publication.name: La Jornada

quote: It acquires an even greater meaning in light of the post-credit slate that reveals that the film is based loosely on stories of the director's grandfather's time in the war. A tribute to a life is one hell of an emotional anchor.
critic.name: Poulomi Das
publication.name: Arré

quote: It's a beautifully made film.
critic.name: Jaby Koay
publication.name: GET Jaby

quote: I thought it was a fantastic movie.
critic.name: Achara Kirk
publication.name: GET Jaby

quote: While narratively simple, 1917 is not devoid of heft.
critic.name: Jorge Ignacio Castillo
publication.name: Planet S Magazine

quote: A hypnotic visual event. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Luis Fernando Galván
publication.name: En Filme

quote: A uniquely powerful take on the carnage of the Great War...a viscerally potent view of a conflict often relegated to the mists of history.
critic.name: Frank Swietek
publication.name: One Guy's Opinion

quote: I was expecting an exciting and technical marvel, but it's an emotional one too. It's breathtaking, in that I didn't want to breathe.
critic.name: Sarah Cartland
publication.name: Caution Spoilers

quote: It's an immersive, visceral and meticulously crafted film that has the emotional stakes to match.
critic.name: Wenlei Ma
publication.name: News.com.au

quote: The adventure turns into a grotesque exaggeration of Murphy's Law - anything that can go wrong happens tenfold.
critic.name: Phil Hall
publication.name: Cinema Crazed

quote: Even if we grant it the distinction of being the first war film to play as one unbroken scene, we may also conclude that it's ultimately less than the sum of ... its part.
critic.name: Jeffrey Overstreet
publication.name: Looking Closer

quote: One of 2019's very best (second only to Marriage Story), 1917 is a war movie whose soulfulness elevates the picture into something approaching grace.
critic.name: Matt Brunson
publication.name: Film Frenzy

quote: 1917 would have been a great silent film, and that's a purposely backhanded compliment.
critic.name: Neil Morris
publication.name: Chatham News + Record (NC)

quote: If nothing else, 1917 is the Mona Lisa of planning. But thankfully it's a lot more than that.
critic.name: Matt Neal
publication.name: ABC Radio (Australia)

quote: The film dazzles at each step, one encounter and adventure after another shot like a set piece, complete in itself with MacKay's stoic presence adding to the pathos and poignancy.
critic.name: Namrata Joshi
publication.name: The Hindu

quote: Roger Deakins is the real star of this movie. The "one shot" is such an incredible feat of filmmaking, 1917 instantly becomes one for the Hollywood history books.
critic.name: Grace Randolph
publication.name: Beyond the Trailer

quote: The film at times is so overwhelmed by its gimmick and its need to push an almost non-existent narrative, that it sacrifices the connective tissue between the audience to keep upping the ante.
critic.name: Dan Tabor
publication.name: Phawker

quote: Mendes's prowling-camera vision of trench and field warfare offers jolts but never surprise; as Roger Deakin's adaptable camera surges through variously lighted locales, one's suspension of disbelief is dispelled by the photogenic stunt.
critic.name: Armond White
publication.name: National Review

quote: 1917 spends a lot of time focused on the crushing monotony of war, but it marries the boring repetition of marching, running and crawling with an urgent plot, and the resulting tension is gripping.
critic.name: Joe Nolan
publication.name: Nashville Scene

quote: The video game perspective ends up being highly distracting in this movie. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Fernanda Solórzano
publication.name: Letras Libres

quote: Sam Mendes. World War I. Roger Deakins. All in one shot. If you love cinema, you are already hooked, but 1917 is worthy of those selling points and then some.
critic.name: Jennifer Heaton
publication.name: Alternative Lens

quote: I can only imagine the effect 1917 will have on audiences that aren't familiar with the techniques Sam Mendes and Roger Deakins are about to unleash upon them.
critic.name: Rohan Naahar
publication.name: Hindustan Times

quote: With its extraordinary long takes and constant focus on the protagonists, it allows the viewers to become even more immersed in the action, inviting total emotional engagement which never lets up.
critic.name: Paula Fleri-Soler
publication.name: Times of Malta

quote: It's hard to watch, but it feels important that we do.
critic.name: Kate Rodger
publication.name: Newshub (NZ)

quote: [A] movie for the ages. I've never seen anything quite like 1917 - and neither have you.
critic.name: Allen Adams
publication.name: The Maine Edge

quote: A visceral experience and visual masterclass, 1917 personalizes the immense scale of the only war to begin on horseback and end in the air.
critic.name: Rubin Safaya
publication.name: AwardsWatch

quote: It's a movie on steroids, cooking up incidents when the truth is bad enough... [But] I succumbed to this thrilling, compelling film.
critic.name: Richard von Busack
publication.name: MetroActive

quote: Mendes' best move in 1917 was tapping Roger Deakins, our greatest living cinematographer, to shoot this intimate story of individual heroism set against the backdrop of an epic conflict.
critic.name: Chris McCoy
publication.name: Memphis Flyer

quote: Cue awards season. This one's a shoo-in for the Oscars, which can't resist imitation, regurgitation and the great-man theory of bunk history.
critic.name: Rick Levin
publication.name: Eugene Weekly (OR)

quote: Do NOT dismiss this as "just another war movie"!
critic.name: Marianna Neal
publication.name: Impression Blend

quote: An epic, immersive and marvelous cinematic achievement that delivers plenty of edge-of-your-seat thrills. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Rene Sanchez
publication.name: Cine Sin Fronteras

quote: 1917 is not as much a war story as it is a true showcase of the power of moving images and the medium of film itself. But I am certain it will be talked about for decades to come.
critic.name: Kent Garrison
publication.name: Mad About Movies Podcast

quote: 1917 is awe-inspiring at every turn and will be immortalised as the moment George Mackay and Dean Charles Chapman made it big on the silver screen.
critic.name: Mark Goodyear
publication.name: Battle Royale With Cheese

quote: It's not always the most comfortable experience. It is, however, a virtually unprecedented one.
critic.name: Rick Kisonak
publication.name: Seven Days

quote: A great movie that shows magical craftsmanship and true love for cinema. [Full review in spanish]
critic.name: David Ocadiz
publication.name: Cinergética

quote: Attempts to thread the needle of a moving anti-war film in that narrow space between...[war as] thrill ride and the filmic wizardry that, when examined too closely, rings as hollow as a war machine rapped with a wrench.
critic.name: Peter Canavese
publication.name: Groucho Reviews

quote: It's a searing, moving film that doesn't have to shout or clamour to get the attention its simplicity and artistry quite justly deserves.
critic.name: Tori Brazier
publication.name: One Room With A View

quote: Telling the story of two very ordinary lance corporals dispatched on a desperate mission behind enemy lines to prevent a massacre of British troops, it is an astonishing and, at times, quite dazzling piece of film-making.
critic.name: Matthew Bond
publication.name: The Mail on Sunday (UK)

quote: [A] film that works best when it takes its focus away from Schofield and Blake and loses itself in extravagant set piece.
critic.name: Hilary A White
publication.name: Sunday Independent (Ireland)

quote: An astonishing achievement in filmmaking, this isn't just another week at the pictures - this is, indeed, one of the greatest war films ever made.
critic.name: Chris Wasser
publication.name: The Herald (Ireland)

quote: If you've seen our corporal dashing down a battlefield perpendicular to an infantry charge, evading exploding mines and mortars as he goes, you've pretty much seen the extent of its climax.
critic.name: Tom Shone
publication.name: Sunday Times (UK)

quote: It is a stunning film, fully deserving of all the gongs that will end up on the already-crowded Mendes mantelpiece.
critic.name: Brian Viner
publication.name: Daily Mail (UK)

quote: The film is thrilling, moving on effectively from one shocking set piece to another, studding the narrative too with starry cameos.
critic.name: David Sexton
publication.name: London Evening Standard

quote: It seems fairly clear that Mendes' aim isn't to give viewers another gritty, realistic experience of what it's like to actually take part in a battle. Strange as it is to say it, there's a fairy-tale quality amid 1917's carnage.
critic.name: Megan Basham
publication.name: WORLD

quote: War remains hell, and "1917" shows us that inferno to devastating effect. Not an easy movie, but certainly a memorable one.
critic.name: Eleanor Ringel Cater
publication.name: Saporta Report (Atlanta)

quote: The sheer practicality of executing this movie is quite phenomenal ... it is a technical tour-de-force.
critic.name: James Marsh
publication.name: RTHK Radio 3

quote: With an almost supernatural attention to detail, Mendes fuses the viewer with a heroic adventure that's so grand the heart is gripped by every beat, every danger, every grief. This war epic is destined to be a global masterwork.
critic.name: Lonita Cook
publication.name: INKansas City Magazine

quote: It's a tense, unnerving ride that accomplishes its goal of translating the first-person experience of war better than any war movies that have come before it. It's a level up.
critic.name: Adam Graham
publication.name: Detroit News

quote: The way in which the film is choreographed, the music is very important...the film actually stops, bringing everyone together in a quasi-religious silence...very moving and effective.
critic.name: Mark Kermode
publication.name: Kermode & Mayo's Film Review

quote: One of the few films this year that succeeds in amplifying the impact of actual events using the power, or distortion, of the camera.
critic.name: Ron Wilkinson
publication.name: It's Just Movies

quote: Though the second half's somewhat theatrical transition into more mythic territory isn't quite as gripping, as the film pushes on towards its Gallipoli-like climax, the tension returns and Mendes pitches the ending just right...
critic.name: Alistair Harkness
publication.name: Scotsman

quote: Considering the subject matter, I was left extremely impressed but not particularly moved.
critic.name: Jamie East
publication.name: The Sun (UK)

quote: Much has been made of Mendes' decision for the film to unfold as if it is one continuous shot, but that mastery of the medium never gets in the way of the human connection with two young men in a seemingly doomed situation.
critic.name: Harry Guerin
publication.name: RTÉ (Ireland)

quote: [T]he result is magnificent.
critic.name: Alison Rowat
publication.name: The Herald (Scotland)

quote: [Sam Mendes'] most complex and ambitious work to date. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: José Martín
publication.name: El antepenúltimo mohicano

quote: The technical skill threatens to drown the narration at times, but the extraordinary strength of the images is there to compensate this narcissistic pulse. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Beatriz Martínez
publication.name: Fotogramas

quote: The film is made up of impressively long shots, which allows the audience to feel as though they're following the cadets' every step. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Diana Álvarez
publication.name: Chilango.com

quote: A picture that blends the surreal nightmarescape of Apocalypse Now with the journey-quest of Saving Private Ryan, torqued up by a race against time -- and, of course, by the rush of watching the filmmakers pull this off on a sheer technical level.
critic.name: Janet Smith
publication.name: Georgia Straight

quote: Technical brio, however, cannot redeem all that is callow and crass in Mendes's movie: the dialogue is pure placeholder stuffing, the approach a clumsy collision of the Assassin's Creed video games and Elem Klimov's Come and See...
critic.name: Nick Pinkerton
publication.name: Film Comment Magazine

quote: In other words, "1917" often seems built more to wow audience than make them feel. And it may well have been a better film set around extended cuts than fully committing to the one-take gimmick.
critic.name: Brad Keefe
publication.name: Columbus Alive

quote: Thematically, 1917 is disappointingly shallow, but technically, it is undeniably impressive.
critic.name: Tom Augustine
publication.name: New Zealand Herald

quote: By relying on technique over most everything else, Mendes takes the focus from the characters, where it truly belongs.
critic.name: Pete Vonder Haar
publication.name: Houston Press

quote: A visual marvel unlike any other, 1917 requires a grandiose, epic cinematic experience to match the vastness of the film itself.
critic.name: Matt Ward
publication.name: Cinematic Considerations

quote: 1917 is breathtaking in every way. A chamber drama tucked inside an exquisitely rendered war epic, 1917 is more heartstopping thriller than traditional war movie.
critic.name: Alex Heeney
publication.name: Seventh Row

quote: Rather empty spectacle; it doesn't really have characters, relationships or emotional stakes ... Schofield has few attributes, other than being a Very Decent British Man, and the film has little to say, other than that British Men are Very Decent.
critic.name: CJ Johnson
publication.name: Film Mafia

quote: ...an unforgettable and immersive viewing experience.
critic.name: Michael Ward
publication.name: Should I See It

quote: 1917 is Absolutely incredible, it's beyond stressful from start to finish. This is a film that demands to be seen in a movie theater.
critic.name: Paul McGuire Grimes
publication.name: KSTP-TV (St. Paul, MN)

quote: 1917 earns its place in the pantheon of great war films. Beyond the spectacle, the film creates beloved characters you'll follow into the face of death.
critic.name: Alan French
publication.name: We Bought a Blog

quote: A rancid propaganda film with video game aesthetics.
critic.name: Louis Proyect
publication.name: Counterpunch.org

quote: Sam Mendes and Roger Deakins' bone-rattling technical virtuosity is matched by an urgent, affecting survival narrative and two exemplary lead performances. 1917 is an artfully visceral, haunting masterwork.
critic.name: Shaun Munro
publication.name: Flickering Myth

quote: Spellbinding in both its compact storytelling and its significant technical contributions making "1917" perhaps the most immersive war picture you've ever seen.
critic.name: Al Alexander
publication.name: The Patriot Ledger

quote: I appreciate that, every once in a while, World War I is remembered, and I appreciate it when good films are made about it. 1917 might not be the best film of the year, but it remains a very good film in its own right.
critic.name: Tim Brennan
publication.name: About Boulder

quote: For all the steel-trap visceral efficiency, it's the more low-key moments that really pack a punch - those moments when we're confronted with the simple human cost of war.
critic.name: Mark Kermode
publication.name: Observer (UK)

quote: A stunning technical achievement, 1917 might just be Sam Mendes' best film yet but this well choreographed series of events play out too neatly to ensure the horrors of war will leave a lasting impact.
critic.name: Josh Wilding
publication.name: ComicBookMovie.com

quote: It's hard not to get stuck on the challenges of the moviemaking rather than the characters that should be the focal point of the film.
critic.name: Louisa Moore
publication.name: Screen Zealots

quote: 1917 is an immersive real-time experience. It's both thrilling and harrowing.
critic.name: Ben Rolph
publication.name: Discussing Film

quote: Give or take a few prominent cameos, its mostly no-name cast, headed by Dean-Charles Chapman and George MacKay, take us through an action-packed assault on the senses.
critic.name: John Urbancich
publication.name: Your Movies (cleveland.com)

quote: Mendes uses the one-shot approach to fully display the horrors of war through the quiet moments. 1917 is a masterpiece of filmmaking.
critic.name: Ian Thomas Malone
publication.name: Ian Thomas Malone

quote: Despite having a thin story, the reason why you should go see 1917 is because of the amazing cinematography.
critic.name: Jason Escamilla
publication.name: EskimoTV

quote: 1917 is a must-see movie, and please, watch it on the big screen.
critic.name: Jeff Mitchell
publication.name: Phoenix Film Festival

quote: I couldn't take my eyes off of the screen.
critic.name: Sara Michelle Fetters
publication.name: MovieFreak.com

quote: It's spectacular to witness for the first 10 minutes before the effect gradually fades out of notice and into its purpose, which is to immerse audiences into the picture.
critic.name: Sarah Gopaul
publication.name: Digital Journal

quote: There have been many (so, so many) films about WW1 before, but never one quite like this, Sir!
critic.name: David 'Mad Dog' Bradley
publication.name: Adelaide Review

quote: I don't know if 1917 will, over time, become a classic among war movies, but it deserves to be included among the best of them. It's a cinematic experience that is at the same time exhilarating, nerve-racking and inspirational.
critic.name: David Stratton
publication.name: The Australian

quote: This feels absolutely authentic... Very small cast and a very simple, straightforward story, which I think makes it so affecting.
critic.name: Charles Solomon
publication.name: FilmWeek (KPCC - NPR Los Angeles)

quote: The film's unique strength lies in its hyper-focused approach. The concentration on one minor mission might feel limiting, but at its best 1917 becomes a refracting lens for the vastness of the Great War's suffering...
critic.name: Alison Gillmor
publication.name: Winnipeg Free Press

quote: From the sole perspective of the filmmaking craft, "1917" is worth a watch.
critic.name: Matthew Rozsa
publication.name: Salon.com

quote: It's tremendously moving. What a terrifically good film.
critic.name: Cath Clarke
publication.name: The Big Issue

quote: Mendes doesn't hit us over the head with politicking but rather lets us form our own opinion as we journey along with the men.
critic.name: Julie Crawford
publication.name: North Shore News (Vancouver, B.C.)

quote: Even more importantly, it serves as a mighty reminder of the inglorious, ruinous cost of war more than 100 years after the so-called "War to End All Wars" proved a sadly inaccurate nickname...
critic.name: Brandy McDonnell
publication.name: The Oklahoman

quote: Horror filmmakers would be wise to study Mendes' set-up and execution - each more dreadful and memorable than any jump scare.
critic.name: Edwin Arnaudin
publication.name: Asheville Movies

quote: The swagger of Mendes' approach echoes and elevates the experience of everyday heroes.
critic.name: Annlee Ellingson
publication.name: L.A. Biz

quote: "1917" is much elevated by its visual and aural elements, most notably the superb production design, sound mixing/editing and Thomas Newman's tense score, enhancing the key moments.
critic.name: Barry Paris
publication.name: Pittsburgh Post-Gazette

quote: Asking director Sam Mendes's latest film to prevent World War III seems like maybe a bit much, but here we are... Short of dropping average Americans into a war zone, nothing can drive home this unique brand of horror quite as much as movies can.
critic.name: Ryan Syrek
publication.name: The Reader (Omaha, NE)

quote: We went to war in a Sieve, indeed. A stunning (anti) war drama, evoking Otto Dix's Der Krieg cycle. A visual tour de force.
critic.name: James Verniere
publication.name: Boston Herald

quote: 1917, shot by the great Roger Deakins, rambles around from open countryside to narrow trenches and tunnels with supple effortlessness.
critic.name: M.V. Moorhead
publication.name: Phoenix Magazine

quote: Sam Mendes' lean, suspenseful World War I drama 1917 pulsates with urgency and purpose.
critic.name: André Hereford
publication.name: Metro Weekly (Washington, DC)

quote: It's a piece of filmmaking bravado, but it will be a shame if it continues to suck up award season oxygen that could go to, say, Little Women or The Farewell.
critic.name: Oscar Goff
publication.name: Boston Hassle

quote: There is a specific scene where Schofield is escaping from pursuing enemy forces, lit almost entirely by flares and done in a single shot, that is basically just Roger Deakins showing off.
critic.name: Matthew Razak
publication.name: Flixist.com

quote: Not since "Saving Private Ryan" has a filmmaker tried to upend conventional war movie standards with bold storytelling techniques in the way Sam Mendes' does with "1917."
critic.name: Nate Adams
publication.name: The Only Critic

quote: With the stakes being high, it did not take me long to become invested in this story.
critic.name: Rosalie Kicks
publication.name: MovieJawn

quote: While Mendes didn't shrink from displaying the vivid imagination of a suburban horndog, he's unwilling to face the imagination of the valorous combatants of "1917."
critic.name: Richard Brody
publication.name: New Yorker

quote: Despite its high-tech credentials and world-beating male cast, Mendes has managed to make a high-gloss war film feel surprisingly personal.
critic.name: Piers Marchant
publication.name: Arkansas Democrat-Gazette

quote: ... Gripping to the point you almost forget about the gimmick that pulls it all together.
critic.name: Greg Maki
publication.name: Star-Democrat (Easton, MD)

quote: What's most impressive about [Sam] Mendes' salute to valor is the seamless synergy of choreography, action and sound.
critic.name: Tom Meek
publication.name: Cambridge Day

quote: For those willing to go on its tough-as-nails, experiential journey, 1917 offers an awe-inducing reward.
critic.name: Bobby Roberts
publication.name: The Stranger (Seattle, WA)

quote: Most war movies build to a big climactic battle, but in "1917," Sam Mendes' relentlessly thrilling ticking-clock film, the goal is to stop the battle from happening, to stop that meat grinder from turning.
critic.name: Rob Thomas
publication.name: Capital Times (Madison, WI)

quote: The plot seems simple but it is the way the story is delivered that makes it so different from other war films.
critic.name: S. Indra Sathiabalan
publication.name: The Sun Daily (Malaysia)

quote: The movie is weakened by two elements. The first is that following Schofield and Blake falters because neither young man is particularly interesting or has a good story backing up his character.
critic.name: Michael Calleri
publication.name: Niagara Gazette

quote: ...once you get over the impressive look of the film, you're still caught up in the story of how war looks to someone fighting it. It's a story that couldn't be more timely.
critic.name: Daniel M. Kimmel
publication.name: North Shore Movies

quote: Of note for the unique single-shot approach, "1917" is also an emotionally arresting and intimate look at the horrors of the Great War.
critic.name: Jonathan W. Hickman
publication.name: The Newnan Times-Herald

quote: Sam Mendes delivers a spectacular look at World War I, but some unforced errors reduce its majesty and scope.
critic.name: Christian Toto
publication.name: HollywoodInToto.com

quote: In the end, 1917 removes the gloss, maintains its heart; brings the audience even closer to being caught in the chaos.
critic.name: Wendy Shreve
publication.name: Featuring Film

quote: Among THE best movies set during WWI ever produced.
critic.name: Steve Crum
publication.name: Crum on Showbiz

quote: Sam Mendes' thrilling WWI drama is an immersive experience leaving the viewer breathless.
critic.name: Joe Friar
publication.name: The Victoria Advocate

quote: 1917's ambitious gambit soon becomes a double-edged sword: it brings us closer to these men, but sets them apart from the collective experiences it seeks to memorialise.
critic.name: Clarisse Loughrey
publication.name: Independent (UK)

quote: The technique does give us a sense of the dreary slog at the front lines, although at times there's something mechanical about the effects and the series of death-defying coincidences that unfold like clockwork.
critic.name: Robert Horton
publication.name: HeraldNet (Everett, WA)

quote: We're supposed to spend the entire film/journey with just two British soldiers, but do we really care about them? Nah.
critic.name: David Harris
publication.name: Spectrum Culture

quote: (I)t has no reason for being. It barely touches on the horror of the trench warfare of the Western Front or the futility of the war itself. 'Paths of Glory' it is not.
critic.name: Tony Medley
publication.name: Tolucan Times

quote: 1917 is an atmospheric appendage of tragedy, horror, soul, and devastation, one whose...evident obsession with technique often overrides other important factors of the creative body.
critic.name: Luke Parker
publication.name: Dr. Filmlove's Film Reviews and Ratings

quote: A very, very good war film about a very, very bad war...Visually, the film is unarguably impressive and Sam Mendes has delivered a cinematic vision of war we haven't quite witnessed before.
critic.name: Jim Schembri
publication.name: 3AW

quote: The result is an agonisingly tense, immensely moving and unusually immersive experience.
critic.name: Demetrios Matheou
publication.name: The Arts Desk

quote: As a war epic, 1917 is rather more low-key than the Sturm und Drang typical of the genre: the film's strength lies in its eerier passages, which linger in the mind with a sense of reflection.
critic.name: Luke Goodsell
publication.name: ABC News (Australia)

quote: The action is swift and heart-pounding.
critic.name: Max Weiss
publication.name: Baltimore Magazine

quote: Sam Mendes' 1917 is a major cinematic achievement that excels on both a technical level and -- most importantly -- an emotional one.
critic.name: Rob Carnevale
publication.name: Indie London

quote: 1917 is a stupendous war movie about WWI that's quite unlike any other in the canon.
critic.name: Erica Abeel
publication.name: Arts Fuse

quote: An exceptional cinematic work of art and craft, Mendes' war drama is most notable for being a powerfully immersive drama that ingeniously also recruits viewers for this dangerous trek through the war zone.
critic.name: Doris Toumarkine
publication.name: FilmDINGHY.com

quote: Both epically sprawling and remarkably intimate, 1917 instantly establishes itself as one of the great war films.
critic.name: Robert W. Butler
publication.name: Butler's Cinema Scene

quote: Creatively conceived and beautifully executed, 1917 is an affecting and tense entry in the pantheon of war movies.
critic.name: Donovan Farley
publication.name: Willamette Week

quote: Halfway through 1917, Sam Mendes's sublime First World War epic that ingeniously unfolds as if it is one continuous shot, there's a sequence of such audacity and beauty that it is impossible not to be overwhelmed by the cinematic assault.
critic.name: Gregory Wakeman
publication.name: The National (UAE)

quote: Audiences who should be absorbed by the physical challenges inherent in the soldiers' mission are likely to be thinking instead of the technical ones faced by the film-makers.
critic.name: Ryan Gilbey
publication.name: New Statesman

quote: When it was being shot only a year ago, 1917 was a phenomenal tribute to a generation almost wiped out in the trenches of World War I. At the moment of release, it has become more timely.
critic.name: Richard Whittaker
publication.name: Austin Chronicle

quote: It's a war film for fans of Downton Abbey. As such, it works splendidly. That doesn't make 1917 a great film.
critic.name: Kristian M. Lin
publication.name: Fort Worth Weekly

quote: "1917" is grand in its scope and haunting in its visuals, but its simplicity is what makes Sam Mendes' film such a resonant portrait of its subject.
critic.name: Josh Terry
publication.name: Deseret News (Salt Lake City)

quote: 1917 is a solemn war movie with popular appeal, the kind of thing that makes award nominations guaranteed. But it's also hollow, lacking the emotional heart that makes the genre more than empty spectacle.
critic.name: Joshua Rivera
publication.name: The Verge

quote: It may feel like a gimmick reserved for video games, but in the hands of Mendes and a talented crew -- including cinematographer Roger Deakins -- this is an emotionally draining and compelling experience.
critic.name: Micheal Compton
publication.name: Bowling Green Daily News

quote: You cannot talk about 1917 without mentioning its technical display. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Yago García
publication.name: Cinemanía (Spain)

quote: Mendes is able to leave his own mark through a humble and ingenious master action. [Full Review in Spanish]
critic.name: Erick Estrada
publication.name: Cinegarage

quote: It is the collaboration of Mendes as writer-director (the screenplay is based on a story his own grandfather recalled from his time in WW1) and Deakins as camera operator that elevates 1917 to the highest plane of mainstream filmmaking.
critic.name: Leigh Paatsch
publication.name: Herald Sun (Australia)

quote: [O]ne of the finest war movies in years, and among the most outstanding that will ever be made about the increasingly distant World War I of a century ago.
critic.name: Michael Smith
publication.name: Tulsa World

quote: But while it is narratively samey, with jeopardy heaped upon jeopardy, and never strays from dramatic convention - it's a race-against-time thriller, as well as an against-all-the-odds one - it is also urgent and involving and we care.
critic.name: Deborah Ross
publication.name: The Spectator

quote: Both a snapshot and a meditation, "1917" is a well-executed glimpse of humanity's ultimate futility.
critic.name: Joe Gross
publication.name: Austin American-Statesman

quote: A slice of prestige British film-making that nimbly avoids accusations of heritage cosiness.
critic.name: Donald Clarke
publication.name: Irish Times

quote: One of the year's best films, '1917' is enveloping and explosive.
critic.name: Roger Tennis
publication.name: Cinemaclips.com

quote: Bracing "1917" nearly loses its way.
critic.name: Charles Koplinski
publication.name: Illinois Times

quote: It should come as no surprise that 1917 will win many awards this season.
critic.name: Allison Rose
publication.name: FlickDirect

quote: One of those films, that after leaving the cinema, one wants to search and learn about all the details of how the original concept was filmed and the final result was achieved. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Fico Cangiano
publication.name: CineXpress

quote: Making a hollow spectacle of war is ignoble. Sometimes it's dangerously irresponsible.
critic.name: Walter Chaw
publication.name: Film Freak Central

quote: This is a movie one does not watch so much as witness. It simply must be seen.
critic.name: Sean Collier
publication.name: Pittsburgh Magazine

quote: The tension is only accentuated by the single-shot conceit, thrusting viewers into the fight - and doing for World War I what Saving Private Ryan did for D-Day.
critic.name: Mike Scott
publication.name: Times-Picayune

quote: If Mendes' film-making has sometimes felt to have not fully outgrown his beginnings in theatre, 1917 is wildly cinematic, a movie that makes you feel the breath of mortality on your neck.
critic.name: Danny Leigh
publication.name: Financial Times

quote: A heartfelt tribute to the sacrifices of our ancestors - a visually impressive and very respectable entry into the war film canon.
critic.name: Anna Smith
publication.name: The List

quote: The finished product is arguably the greatest single-take illusion in cinema history. And it's also the best movie about the Great War since Lawrence of Arabia in 1962.
critic.name: Cameron Meier
publication.name: Orlando Weekly

quote: It is a triumph of immersive storytelling.
critic.name: John Lui
publication.name: The Straits Times (Singapore)

quote: There are problems with the single-take approach, all of them destined to take the viewer out of the story.
critic.name: Sean P. Means
publication.name: Salt Lake Tribune

quote: War is much on the minds of people right now, and "1917" is a good reminder, flaws and all, of what that really entails.
critic.name: Bill Goodykoontz
publication.name: Arizona Republic

quote: It's cinema as a VR headset, with all the expressive qualities of the art replaced by a dull literal-mindedness, a quote-unquote immersive trip into unconvincing verisimilitude that makes a lousy substitute for drama.
critic.name: Sean Burns
publication.name: The ARTery

quote: Masterfully choreographed by Mendes, the action is counterbalanced with intimate moments and random encounters, including unexpected cameos by Andrew Scott, Benedict Cumberbatch and Richard Madden.
critic.name: Larushka Ivan-Zadeh
publication.name: Metro Newspaper (UK)

quote: Worth seeing for the cinematography alone (thanks Roger Deakins); but also has a gripping storyline and solid acting performances by the two male leads.
critic.name: Jackie K. Cooper
publication.name: jackiekcooper.com

quote: This action-packed film that looks like it was all shot with one continuous camera exposure is an emotional, compelling and inspiring hero's journey through the nightmare setting of trench warfare.
critic.name: Robert Roten
publication.name: Laramie Movie Scope

quote: Full of thrills and spills yet surprisingly intimate and personal, 1917 is a breathtaking, profound tour de force, easily sealing its position as one of the greatest war films of all time.
critic.name: Jeanmarie Tan
publication.name: The New Paper (Singapore)

quote: A visceral war epic that manages to be bitterly anti-war at heart while also honoring fleeting moments of heroism of and grace.
critic.name: Andrew Wyatt
publication.name: The Lens

quote: 1917 is a film that you approach as a technical marvel and then are absorbed by its breathtaking humanity.
critic.name: Christopher Lloyd
publication.name: The Film Yap

quote: Harrowing, tragic, humbling and heroically played out.
critic.name: Andiee Paviour
publication.name: Nobody's Reading This But Me

quote: '1917' is a film that sticks with you long after it's over.
critic.name: Jamie Broadnax
publication.name: Black Girl Nerds

quote: Deakins' camera never wavers, effortlessly floating from one stunning composition to another.
critic.name: Clint Worthington
publication.name: The Spool

quote: It's difficult to fully invest in the drama when you're constantly being prompted to think about the mind-boggling logistics behind the filmmaking.
critic.name: Philip Concannon
publication.name: Sight & Sound

quote: The lasting memories of this film combine the two actors enduring scene after scene of astonishingly wrenching and suspenseful episodes along with the intimate long-shot technique.
critic.name: Linda and Al Lerner
publication.name: Movies and Shakers

quote: Oscar-winning director Sam Mendes and Oscar-winning cinematographer Roger Deakins have created one of the most visually stunning war movies in modern cinema.
critic.name: Kiko Martinez
publication.name: San Antonio Current

quote: The result is an unparalleled and impressive spectacle, to which the eyes are riveted.
critic.name: Uri Klein
publication.name: Haaretz

quote: MacKay and Chapman disappear into their roles, pulling us into the story.
critic.name: Moira MacDonald
publication.name: Seattle Times

quote: A soldier asks: "Do you know where we are?" Keeping with the "Grand Theft Auto: Écoust-Saint-Mein" aesthetic, you can guess which rock-song retort rolls through your mind. Full of empty razzle-dazzle, "1917" has as many dimensions as noticeable cuts.
critic.name: Nick Rogers
publication.name: Midwest Film Journal

quote: A huge technical achievement. An immersive war film that's low on plot but high on blistering action.
critic.name: Greg Wetherall
publication.name: Little White Lies

quote: The panic that festers throughout '1917' comes in small increments, but it's how Deakins' camera tracks them at every turn as it pulls back little by little to reveal the true scale of the horror and the shock of World War I.
critic.name: Brian Lloyd
publication.name: entertainment.ie

quote: If Mendes made 1917 without the gimmickry, he could have made something special that effectively honoured the true story. Instead, this is a mere technical exercise that everybody will forget about as soon as awards season is over.
critic.name: Alistair Ryder
publication.name: The Digital Fix

quote: It's a tribute to heroism with an abbreviated emotional outreach, yet it's consistently impressive to look at and to sense the scale of.
critic.name: Nguyên Lê
publication.name: InSession Film

quote: While 1917 doesn't have a ton of layers in its storytelling or its characters, it's a film that certainly makes up for it with exquisite visuals and glorious music.
critic.name: Chris Sawin
publication.name: Bounding Into Comics

quote: Not that the cinematography, by the great Roger Deakins, isn't impressive. But eventually it's just a gimmick.
critic.name: Stephen Silver
publication.name: Splice Today

quote: 1917 is a beautiful film, and an important one, held back only by the very gimmick that makes most of it work.
critic.name: Tom Santilli
publication.name: Movie Show Plus

quote: Technically, it's absolutely extraordinary, but it says very little about the war itself, or war in general, or much at all, which is a missed opportunity.
critic.name: Daniel Rutledge
publication.name: Flicks.co.nz

quote: There is just something about this journey, about the need for Lance Corporal Schofield to find Lt. Joseph Blake. It's something that I would see again and again.
critic.name: Rachel Leishman
publication.name: The Mary Sue

quote: A fresh perspective on a familiar horror story.
critic.name: Vicky Roach
publication.name: Daily Telegraph (Australia)

quote: The action is propulsive and unrelenting, greatly enhanced by the 'time running out' motif of real-time plot.
critic.name: Brett McCracken
publication.name: The Gospel Coalition

quote: This film, though, with its gritty reality, is so much more -- a social commentary, even.
critic.name: Chuck Yarborough
publication.name: Cleveland Plain Dealer

quote: The overall impact of 1917 is simply breathtaking, horrifying, appalling. It offers a compelling version of what a day in the war might have felt like for two soldiers.
critic.name: Paul Byrnes
publication.name: Sydney Morning Herald

quote: However well-intentioned its spectacle, 1917 feels fundamentally wrong-disrespectful to a historical reality in its very attempts to evoke it.
critic.name: Jonathan Romney
publication.name: Film Comment Magazine

quote: Will have broad appeal and a long afterlife on Sunday afternoon TV, subject to the odd trim for language.
critic.name: Ed Whitfield
publication.name: The Ooh Tray

quote: Union general William Tecumseh Sherman once said, "War is hell." Sam Mendes with "1917" says, "Hold my beer."
critic.name: Cary Darling
publication.name: Houston Chronicle

quote: A triumphant piece of filmmaking, all bravado and ambition, expertly realised at the hands of Sam Mendes and cinematographer Roger Deakins.
critic.name: Iana Murray
publication.name: The Skinny

quote: A nerve-shredding, eye-popping odyssey through the horrors of World War One.
critic.name: Andy Lea
publication.name: Daily Star (UK)

quote: Its technical aspects are so uniformly remarkable that one almost becomes so caught up in the nail-biting high-wire act on display that it's easy to miss the more human elements of the story it sought to illuminate in the first place.
critic.name: Matthew Lucas
publication.name: The Dispatch (Lexington, NC)

quote: As far as 'single-take' movies go, 1917 is one of the best.
critic.name: Simon Miraudo
publication.name: Student Edge

quote: It's visually spectacular and undoubtedly a polished feat of filmmaking craft.
critic.name: Peter Gray
publication.name: Brisbanista

quote: It's only the beginning of 2020 and I am already very clear that '1917' is going to be one of the best films of the year. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Mikel Zorrilla
publication.name: Espinof

quote: A triumph of style, and a beautiful looking film, it's just a pity it didn't have more to say.
critic.name: Anthony O'Connor
publication.name: FILMINK (Australia)

quote: A war film that will take you on both a physical and emotional journey, 1917 is likely to be remembered as one of the great movies of 2020.
critic.name: James Croot
publication.name: Stuff.co.nz

quote: Awe-inspiring, terrifying, yet utterly gorgeous.
critic.name: Kelly Vance
publication.name: East Bay Express

quote: 1917 qualifies as an impressive piece of immersive cinema.
critic.name: Robert Denerstein
publication.name: Denerstein Unleashed

quote: You will be awed by the cinematography, the directing, the acting, the storytelling, the editing, the score - every aspect of this film is impressive and moving.
critic.name: Lisa Johnson Mandell
publication.name: AtHomeInHollywood.com

quote: A film, or any work, can be extraordinarily well-wrought and still feel a bit pointless. An abundance of fiddly labor, little flicks of the wrist, all meant to leave us impressed by the challenge of the very doing of the work.
critic.name: Rob Gonsalves
publication.name: eFilmCritic.com

quote: 1917 is a visceral experience that should be watched in the theatre on the biggest IMAX screen you can find.
critic.name: Lauren Veneziani
publication.name: WBAL-TV (Baltimore)

quote: Chapman and McKay deserve salute for their work as leads. Through their weary eyes and baby faces, the duo project the horrors of their Homeric journey and inspiring sacrifice.
critic.name: Asher Luberto
publication.name: L.A. Weekly

quote: Mendes has created a profoundly moving and utterly immersive piece of filmmaking, proving one of this year's cinematic highlights.
critic.name: Nicola Austin
publication.name: We Have a Hulk

quote: The use of a camera seamlessly following two men through the trenches, barbed wire, and horrors of No Man's Land is a sight we didn't know we needed to see. We need to see it. Because it adds to the heap of things about war that we should never forget.
critic.name: Mark Jackson
publication.name: Epoch Times

quote: 1917 is more than a film, it's an immersive experience that leaves you exhausted when it's over, in the best possible way.
critic.name: Mike McGranaghan
publication.name: Aisle Seat

quote: While the story might not be anything special, the production is genuinely shocking in how good it is.
critic.name: Brandon Zachary
publication.name: CBR

quote: The digital effects are utterly invisible, the camerawork astonishing and the sound mix visceral, but it's [George] MacKay's face that tells the story, even though he never seems to be acting at all.
critic.name: Rich Cline
publication.name: Shadows on the Wall

quote: Two of this film's biggest strengths are Newman's score and MacKay's commanding central performance, as well as the visual spectacle. 1917 has done an amazing job at taking a war from 100 years ago and turning it into an urgent, immersive experience.
critic.name: Fiona Underhill
publication.name: JumpCut Online

quote: 1917 is two hours of: Look at these broken bodies but also admire how they look staged in this buttery morning light and emerald green fields.
critic.name: Sarah Marrs
publication.name: Lainey Gossip

quote: This is a sensorial barrage, an overwhelming immersion that only cinema can offer.
critic.name: Stephen Garrett
publication.name: Book & Film Globe

quote: This is a tremendous technical achievement and I was just dazzled the whole time.
critic.name: Christy Lemire
publication.name: FilmWeek (KPCC - NPR Los Angeles)

quote: You get a sense of what it was like in the trenches in World War I.
critic.name: Tim Cogshell
publication.name: FilmWeek (KPCC - NPR Los Angeles)

quote: Mendes takes this fraught story to a higher level by shooting it as though it was a single moving shot and the effect is utterly mesmerising.
critic.name: Anne Brodie
publication.name: What She Said

quote: So much of the best film craftsmanship functions on an almost subliminal level, but in 1917 crafts are put front and center in a starring role, and the results are extraordinary.
critic.name: Ciara Wardlow
publication.name: Pajiba

quote: Rightfully earns its place as one of the all-time greatest war films and its gripping presentation ensure it won't be forgotten anytime soon.
critic.name: Jeffrey Lyles
publication.name: Lyles' Movie Files

quote: Director Sam Mendes [personalizes] the experience through two young British soldiers sent on a harrowing, high-stakes, night-long mission, he creates a film that is tense, exhilarating and profoundly moving.
critic.name: Caryn James
publication.name: BBC.com

quote: 1917 is not a typical war movie, for those of you who don't care for the genre. It's a beautiful ode to the brave men who did everything they could to save others --- and the sacrifices they faced.
critic.name: Jeanne Kaplan
publication.name: Kaplan vs. Kaplan

quote: That this movie is so simplistic in its approach, and turns out to be so staggering in its emotional power, is a tribute to not only the acting, writing and direction. The cinematography and the music are of equal importance.
critic.name: David Kaplan
publication.name: Kaplan vs. Kaplan

quote: 1917 is a full-body exercise that will take quite a while to shake, and may even leave you gasping for breath
critic.name: Steven Prokopy
publication.name: Third Coast Review

quote: Keeping a take going for an entire movie, though, is a mistake. It redirects the attention from the story to the technique. To be slightly rude about it, it makes Sam Mendes, not his characters, the star of the movie.
critic.name: Kyle Smith
publication.name: National Review

quote: Yet the tale unfolds with considerable sensitivity, offering plenty of haunting images while capturing the chaos and fear of trench warfare -- especially through the eyes of MacKay, in a genuine breakout performance.
critic.name: Brian Lowry
publication.name: CNN.com

quote: Mendes, Deakins and Smith's visual experimentation hits a couple of hurdles, but for the most part, it helps achieve that vision beautifully.
critic.name: Abby Olcese
publication.name: Crooked Marquee

quote: We care about its people, we understand its stakes, we believe in the world it presents to us. It may not tell us anything new about war or the people who fight it, but it also doesn't tell us anything that doesn't feel true.
critic.name: Abbie Bernstein
publication.name: Assignment X

quote: This story would be just one more war story if not for the way it's told.
critic.name: Martha K. Baker
publication.name: KDHX (St. Louis)

quote: It is an unusual epic told in a unique way that manages to engage even as it struggles to become more than just a cinematic exercise.
critic.name: Jordan Riefe
publication.name: Truthdig

quote: An uncommonly good antiwar film about two British soldiers in World War I sent on a mission of mercy.
critic.name: Frederic and Mary Ann Brussat
publication.name: Spirituality & Practice

quote: Sam Mendes, has similarly taken top technology - and the best cinematography - to give us a different, equally compelling look at that cruel war, through the eyes of two ordinary soldiers asked to perform an extraordinary task.
critic.name: Jocelyn Noveck
publication.name: Associated Press

quote: Many films claim to be immersive but this one genuinely is. It was inspired by the stories Mendes heard from his grandfather, a combat veteran. The younger man has done his family proud, and given us one of the finest films of 2019.
critic.name: Leonard Maltin
publication.name: leonardmaltin.com

quote: Sam Mendes brings all his skills as a theatre director to make a film that is both epic and surprisingly intimate...
critic.name: Sarah Boslaugh
publication.name: TheArtsStl

quote: ...an ambitious and thrilling war film, a filmic formal exercise with gumption.
critic.name: Joel Mayward
publication.name: Cinemayward

quote: '1917' is a fluid marriage of film technique and storytelling. With its lived-in situations, committed performances and creative direction, we witness a war movie that is sure to cement itself among the most decorated line of the genre.
critic.name: Preston Barta
publication.name: Denton Record-Chronicle

quote: Mendes has made a film that feels wholly alive. It's a carefully polished picture, not one that strives for gritty realism. But its inherent devotion to life and beauty is part of its power...
critic.name: Stephanie Zacharek
publication.name: TIME Magazine

quote: A craft masterpiece: pretty much every major aspect of filmmaking is represented by some of the best work of 2019.
critic.name: Tim Brayton
publication.name: Alternate Ending

quote: In "1917," creators used their enormous technical talent to rationalize and justify an irrational, unjustifiable war.
critic.name: Noah Berlatsky
publication.name: NBC News THINK

quote: Despite the film's salient features, "1917" feels oddly underwhelming. It might succeed in making viewers as exhausted as the characters, but it lacks the emotional punch this story requires to make it a lasting impact.
critic.name: Gary M. Kramer
publication.name: Salon.com

quote: A completely engrossing, captivating and immersive experience filled with Deakins-created visuals that will be seared into your memory for some time to come. (Full Content Review for Parents - Violence, Profanity, etc. - also Available)
critic.name: Jim Judy
publication.name: Screen It!

quote: Sitting through it is like watching someone else playing a video game for two solid hours, and not an especially compelling one at that.
critic.name: Peter Sobczynski
publication.name: RogerEbert.com

quote: ... the theater was how this was meant to be seen: no stopping, no respite, and no escape... a two-hour no-cutaway immersion into war.
critic.name: Kevin A. Ranson
publication.name: MovieCrypt.com

quote: The movie never breaks its rules and never loses sight of its objective.
critic.name: James Berardinelli
publication.name: ReelViews

quote: The filmmakers don't shy from set pieces that would be astonishing even without their central gimmick. They set themselves a challenge for "1917", and met it in ways sure to be talked about by lovers of cinema for quite a while.
critic.name: Bob Mondello
publication.name: NPR

quote: A carefully organized and sanitized war picture... that turns one of the most catastrophic episodes in modern times into an exercise in preening showmanship.
critic.name: Manohla Dargis
publication.name: New York Times

quote: 1917 is a hauntingly realistic recap of WWI through the eyes of two soldiers desperately attempting to prevent more tragedy in an already intense war. Hands down Best Picture contender for 2020!
critic.name: Carla Renata
publication.name: The Curvy Film Critic

quote: 1917 does an amazing thing - it reminds us of the wonder of moviemaking in a time where CGI has all be robbed us from the ability to ever be wowed anymore.
critic.name: Bill Watters
publication.name: Aggressive Comix

quote: Gripping, heart-stopping, blood- and mud-soaked, immersive and unforgettable...
critic.name: Richard Roeper
publication.name: Chicago Sun-Times

quote: 1917 is not a Terrence Malick joint with deep meditation on the meaning of war, life, or death, but rather surrounds the viewer in the urgent firsthand experience.
critic.name: Bradley Gibson
publication.name: Film Threat

quote: The film's formal trickery is impressive, to be sure.
critic.name: Mark Dujsik
publication.name: Mark Reviews Movies

quote: The unbroken shot format is intended to open this world up, but ultimately encases it within a rigid proscenium
critic.name: Jason McKiernan
publication.name: Film Racket

quote: The film has many standout moments, but Mendes' decision to film this...as a virtual one take à la "Birdman" turns his movie into a videogame where our heroes move forward across a varying landscape stopping for episodic incidents to unfold.
critic.name: Laura Clifford
publication.name: Reeling Reviews

quote: A stunning feat of cinematography, production design and performance moving seamlessly as one piece.
critic.name: Katie Walsh
publication.name: Tribune News Service

quote: Roger Deakins has long been one of film's all time great cinematographers. "1917" is his finest hour and one of the most stunning technical achievements in ages.
critic.name: Joey Magidson
publication.name: Hollywood News

quote: The artifice of the aesthetic premise overwhelms any of the film's other intentions.
critic.name: Alison Willmore
publication.name: New York Magazine/Vulture

quote: A first-class war drama.
critic.name: Dennis Schwartz
publication.name: Dennis Schwartz Movie Reviews

quote: It musters extraordinary technical daring in the service of a homily that boils down yet again to simply, "War is Hell."
critic.name: Chris Klimek
publication.name: NPR

quote: Deakins and Mendes have whipped up a barrage of horrific images and some of the year's most spellbinding moments.
critic.name: Kent Turner
publication.name: Film-Forward.com

quote: Mendes'1917 is a special movie; the kind that arrives once a decade not once a year.
critic.name: Travis Hopson
publication.name: Punch Drunk Critics

quote: It is a stunning and savage existential exercise, and a thing of overwhelming poetic beauty.
critic.name: Andrea Chase
publication.name: Killer Movie Reviews

quote: It's certainly not the first of its kind, but nevertheless a work of profound artistry and magnificent technical accomplishment.
critic.name: Christopher Llewellyn Reed
publication.name: Film Festival Today

quote: '1917' unfolds like an overstuffed video game. It becomes rather silly and farfetched the further toward the front it proceeds. The movie features some decent action sequences, which are presented sterilely and unimaginatively ...
critic.name: Bob Bloom
publication.name: Journal and Courier (Lafayette, IN)

quote: One of the best movies of 2019.
critic.name: Peter Howell
publication.name: Toronto Star

quote: It's not really the characters or story that make the film special: it's the technical presentation.
critic.name: Leigh Monson
publication.name: Birth.Movies.Death.

quote: What promises to be "Saving Private Ryan" meets, um, "Climax" unwittingly plays out like some World War I-set video game à la "Verdun."
critic.name: Martin Tsai
publication.name: Critic's Notebook

quote: In one of the best war films of all time, director Sam Mendes brilliantly delivers a story of two WWI soldiers on a mission that's a stunning technical accomplishment that unfurls as one single take - and a deeply felt tale of heroism under fire.
critic.name: Peter Travers
publication.name: Rolling Stone

quote: 1917 is a visual wonder, but it's also a tense piece of effective genre filmmaking that puts its audience right in the trenches without a means to escape.
critic.name: Steve Katz
publication.name: Bullz-Eye.com

quote: A gripping human drama, a bracing history lesson, a bruising survival saga and a blowout adventure yarn--and a jaw-dropping marvel of astonishing, immersive filmmaking.
critic.name: Neil Pond
publication.name: Parade Magazine

quote: Sam Mendes' 1917 is a masterpiece achievement in filmmaking and without a doubt one of the best war films to ever be made.
critic.name: Danielle Solzman
publication.name: Solzy at the Movies

quote: Mendes' intense saga about a perilous two-man mission during the Great War brings the terror of battle thrillingly to bear.
critic.name: Kim Hughes
publication.name: Original Cin

quote: By the time it ends, Mendes has built within the audience an intense desire to see the men's message successfully delivered, and like a true dramatist, Mendes milks it for every drop of tension. He does not blow his big finish.
critic.name: Mick LaSalle
publication.name: San Francisco Chronicle

quote: The film has a lot of propulsive energy that I found pretty delightful.
critic.name: Amy Nicholson
publication.name: FilmWeek (KPCC - NPR Los Angeles)

quote: Despite all the gimmickry and the cameos, there's some real heart here.
critic.name: Wade Major
publication.name: FilmWeek (KPCC - NPR Los Angeles)

quote: [A] disappointment.
critic.name: Marie Asner
publication.name: Phantom Tollbooth

quote: It's as overwhelming as Dunkirk, and infinitely more personal.
critic.name: Tim Appelo
publication.name: AARP Movies for Grownups

quote: Every war is hell, no matter when it was fought, but 1917, which is about a war far removed from contemporary reality, turns out to the best war picture since Saving Private Ryan.
critic.name: Rex Reed
publication.name: Observer

quote: Deakins' work here is, per usual, superlative.
critic.name: Nick Johnston
publication.name: Vanyaland

quote: A truly impressive war movie, one that ranks with the genre's very best.
critic.name: Jeffrey M. Anderson
publication.name: Combustible Celluloid

quote: As a war film, 1917 doesn't have much in the way of new ideas to offer - and maybe there aren't any for the genre now - but it's so elegantly crafted it takes the breath away.
critic.name: Joshua Starnes
publication.name: VitalThrills.com

quote: One needn't be British to feel the epic loss and grief of 1917, thanks to some very committed performances, the intimacy achieved by the movie's style and camera and Mr. Mendes's obvious devotion to what he's doing.
critic.name: John Anderson
publication.name: Wall Street Journal

quote: Think Kubrick's 'Paths of Glory' crossed with Spielberg's 'Saving Private Ryan,' and you'll be in the grim yet somehow exhilarating vicinity of this inevitable Best Picture Oscar contender.
critic.name: Glenn Lovell
publication.name: CinemaDope

quote: 1917 stresses the idea that war is hell. To put such a heavy responsibility on two young soldiers...is utterly horrifying. Of course, it's also thrilling, and therefore gives moviegoers one hell of a film experience at the cineplex.
critic.name: Jeff York
publication.name: Creative Screenwriting

quote: An immersive war film driven by bravura camerawork and spectacular effects.
critic.name: Rafer Guzman
publication.name: Newsday

quote: 1917 is the peak of what's possible right now cinematically.
critic.name: Dan Murrell
publication.name: Screen Junkies
