quote: A gorgeous display of immersive filmmaking that artistically is mostly empty calories.
critic.name: Vincent Mancini
publication.name: FilmDrunk

quote: The taut and chilling imagery in 1917 grab viewers by the throat and releases them just long enough to gasp for air.
critic.name: Courtney Small
publication.name: Cinema Axis

quote: 1917 not only works as a thrilling piece of filmmaking but a cinematic work of art relying on performance as much as spectacle.
critic.name: Aaron Neuwirth
publication.name: We Live Entertainment

quote: Skyfall director Sam Mendes and cinematographer Roger Deakins re-team for the filmmaking answer to "who can hold their breath the longest?"
critic.name: Radheyan Simonpillai
publication.name: NOW Toronto

quote: Sam Mendes' epic WWI drama is a towering achievement in so many ways . A remarkable film that looks like no other.
critic.name: Pete Hammond
publication.name: Deadline Hollywood Daily

quote: Mendes makes a striking film, but not a consistently enthralling one, finding the production's gimmick occasionally throttling its pace and intensity.
critic.name: Brian Orndorf
publication.name: Blu-ray.com

quote: "1917" concentrates its adrenaline into a relentless experience that will strafe your senses.
critic.name: Don Shanahan
publication.name: 25YL (25 Years Later)

quote: Unique WWI epic has brutal war violence, smoking.
critic.name: Tara McNamara
publication.name: Common Sense Media

quote: Mendes and Deakins have engineered an astonishing war film that's equally as thrilling visually as it is narratively.
critic.name: Dustin Chase
publication.name: Texas Art & Film

quote: Its pace is as propulsive as the film's conceit is ambitious. It all leads up to a climactic battlefield dash that should justifiably become a staple of war-cinema highlight reels for decades to come.
critic.name: Barry Hertz
publication.name: Globe and Mail

quote: What might have been easily dismissed as little more than a simplistic stunt, instead becomes a potent and unforgettable piece of cinema.
critic.name: Ann Hornaday
publication.name: Washington Post

quote: A highly convincing welter of dirt, exhaustion, and decay...
critic.name: Anthony Lane
publication.name: New Yorker

quote: Emotionally hollow, 1917 is the big what if of 2019.
critic.name: Robert Daniels
publication.name: 812filmreviews

quote: 1917 makes up for its simplistic, familiar message with tremendous execution just about everywhere else.
critic.name: Jon Negroni
publication.name: The Young Folks

quote: Just like Blake and Schofield, you are disoriented and on high alert the whole time.
critic.name: Chris Taylor
publication.name: Mashable

quote: With incredibly immersive visuals, courtesy of the great Roger Deakins, 1917 is a major cinematic achievement on the technical level, even while the script retreads classic war film themes without anything new to say.
critic.name: Matt Joseph
publication.name: We Got This Covered

quote: The great strength of 1917 remains in its mixing of craftsmanship and storytelling, Mendes and co. managing to smuggle in meaningful thematic complexities against the backdrop of such a flashy technical masterwork.
critic.name: Matt Oakes
publication.name: Silver Screen Riot

quote: 1917 is an intense, immersive experience told from the eyes of these two men. You'll hold your breath when they do, gasp when they do, and jump when they do.
critic.name: Hannah Lodge
publication.name: Screen Rex

quote: Compelling and immersive, an audacious cinematic adventure.
critic.name: Susan Granger
publication.name: SSG Syndicate

quote: I was rooting for the characters and riveted by every turn in their journey
critic.name: Rachel Wagner
publication.name: rachelsreviews.net

quote: The film proves once again that war is hell, but the aftermath can be just as visceral and thoughtful.
critic.name: Brian Truitt
publication.name: USA Today

quote: A breathtaking spectacle that's both grippingly tense and powerfully moving, this is a film that already stamps it claim on becoming a classic of the war genre.
critic.name: Doug Jamieson
publication.name: The Jam Report

quote: 1917 becomes limited in its capacity for something visceral without deeper established roots in its characters.
critic.name: Chris Feil
publication.name: Filmmixtape

quote: 1917 is well-acted and an undeniable technical achievement, yet its real-time storytelling is both the film's greatest strength and biggest problem.
critic.name: Sandy Schaefer
publication.name: Screen Rant

quote: There is also a remarkable central performance from George MacKay, who carries the picture, through moments of darkness, joy and sadness.
critic.name: Kaleem Aftab
publication.name: Cineuropa

quote: 1917, holds rank alongside the likes of Apocalypse Now, Saving Private Ryan, and Dunkirk. Let's hope 1917 marks the moment at which Hollywood recognizes its neglect of an underserved genre.
critic.name: Frank Wilkins
publication.name: Reel Reviews

quote: Mendes captures the immediacy of the trenches, the mechanical nature of war but also the vulnerable circumstances that can save or lose a life in a fraction of a second.
critic.name: Ella Kemp
publication.name: Culture Whisper

quote: A visceral big screen experience, full of tension and emotional impact from beginning to end. Outstanding filmmaking! [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Nestor Bentancor
publication.name: Nestor Cine Desde Hollywood

quote: War is hell no matter what perspective you look at it. However, Sam Mendes chose 1917 to show a perspective we will never forget. [Full review in Spanish]
critic.name: Ruben Peralta Rigaud
publication.name: Cocalecas

quote: Tense, powerful and breathtaking, 1917 is a visceral movie you won't forget in a hurry - and it's the first must-see movie of next year.
critic.name: Ian Sandwell
publication.name: Digital Spy

quote: No, the long takes don't transform "1917" into the cinema event of 2019.
critic.name: Roger Moore
publication.name: Movie Nation

quote: Sam Mendes delivers the film of his career by mashing up the survivalist thrills of The Revenant with the helter-skelter mayhem of a shoot'em'up video game, and setting it during the Great War.
critic.name: Kevin Maher
publication.name: Times (UK)

quote: While a bit too stiff in its execution to be the masterpiece many hail it as, its adrenaline rush nature almost had me believing it was nonetheless.
critic.name: Jared Mobarak
publication.name: Jaredmobarak.com

quote: Mendes and Deakins present a vision of uninterrupted chaos, equipped with a unique blend of personal pathos and visual bravado. Its cumulative impact is undeniable.
critic.name: Josh Martin
publication.name: Film Inquiry

quote: Might just be the most captivating and intense war film you've seen in decades.
critic.name: Rob Hunter
publication.name: Film School Rejects

quote: Co-written by Krysty Wilson-Cairns, 1917 is a straightforward but wildly creative drama set in WWI. A gripping awards contender with outstanding cinematography.
critic.name: Brigid Presecky
publication.name: FF2 Media

quote: This film is a remarkable achievement.
critic.name: Chris Stuckmann
publication.name: ChrisStuckmann.com

quote: One of the most exhilarating, audacious and powerful war films in years. It ranks up there with All Quiet on the Western Front, Apocalypse Now and Saving Private Ryan.
critic.name: Avi Offer
publication.name: NYC Movie Guru

quote: [I]t's hard to totally invest in the plight of these frazzled grunts when they're both filmed and characterized like video-game avatars, guided from one "level" to the next.
critic.name: A.A. Dowd
publication.name: AV Club

quote: Sam Mendes homage to his grandfather's stories of World War I has splashed onto the screen as a modern day video game. For better and for worse.
critic.name: Joanna Langfield
publication.name: The Movie Minute

quote: Not many films leave you exhausted, but 1917 put you in the action. It was draining, horrifying, and an amazing piece of cinema. Give Deakins all the awards!
critic.name: EJ Moreno
publication.name: Flickering Myth

quote: A mesmeric glimpse of history defined more by the quiet isolation of trench warfare than machine-gun projectiles whizzing by every couple of seconds.
critic.name: Matt Donato
publication.name: Atom Insider

quote: A century ago, World War I propelled history into an unseen state-of-the-art era of warfare, and now, 1917 closes out this current decade as a masterpiece that will thrust the genre into a brave new era.
critic.name: Dan Pfleegor
publication.name: Consequence

quote: A glorious and breathtaking cinematic experience that examines the unbroken resilience of the human spirit.
critic.name: Rendy Jones
publication.name: Rendy Reviews

quote: It's both stylish and gimmicky, while also emotionally tense and incredibly clever, resulting in a unique cinematic experience that's frequently harrowing, propulsive, and often emotional excruciating.
critic.name: Douglas Davidson
publication.name: Elements of Madness

quote: 1917 is a brilliantly filmed World War I movie, that showcases a wide range of atrocities of war outside of the spectrum of one-note bloody violence. This film is agonizing, believable and unapologetic in telling a real-time story.
critic.name: Vincent Schilling
publication.name: Indian Country Today

quote: ...emphasizes space and distance in a way that's undeniably immersive.
critic.name: Josh Larsen
publication.name: LarsenOnFilm

quote: 1917 is an astonishing cinematic achievement. Director Sam Mendes and cinematographer Roger Deakins elevate filmmaking artistry through technical brilliance and old fashioned, gritty storytelling.
critic.name: Julian Roman
publication.name: MovieWeb

quote: Almost every frame of 1917 is something you could blow-up and put on your wall, it's such a beautifully lit and lensed picture.
critic.name: Kyle Pinion
publication.name: The Beat

quote: 'Once Upon a Time on the Western Front', as you could subtitle Sam Mendes's nerve-fraying rollercoaster of a war movie, is a simple men-on-a-mission dressed up with all the technical bells and whistles at the director's disposal.
critic.name: Philip De Semlyen
publication.name: Time Out

quote: World War I was a war of meters won over days and weeks, and 1917becomes a microcosm of this idea, showing the struggle for every step these men take.
critic.name: Brian Roan
publication.name: The Film Stage

quote: Less a fully-realized story and more a beautifully-executed experiment, leaving me astonished at the spectacle, but ultimately feeling empty.
critic.name: Tyler Smith
publication.name: Battleship Pretension

quote: You might make your own heroic 300-yard dash following 1917 just to watch it again; it's ambitious with much to take away and contemplate over, equal parts unforgettable and frustrating
critic.name: Robert Kojder
publication.name: Flickering Myth

quote: Mendes' new movie is an undeniable technical achievement, but it's all in service to the story.
critic.name: Matt Goldberg
publication.name: Collider

quote: It's a staggering technical achievement, one that will see Roger Deakins retaining his unofficial Greatest Living Cinematographer crown.
critic.name: Matt Maytum
publication.name: Total Film

quote: Although 1917's filmmaking very much brings attention to itself, it's an astonishing piece of filmmaking, portraying war with enormous panache. This is big-screen bravado, and then some.
critic.name: Alex Godfrey
publication.name: Empire Magazine

quote: The most thrilling and haunting details here are actively undermined by the chief technical gimmick of the film.
critic.name: Jake Cole
publication.name: Slant Magazine

quote: The proximity and intimacy of 1917 render the characters' journey more visceral and more frightening, resulting in the catharsis landing with the force of a hammer.
critic.name: Jason Bailey
publication.name: The Playlist

quote: The story is simple in nature... but epic in execution.
critic.name: Jeremy Jahns
publication.name: JeremyJahns.com

quote: One-take movies are nothing new, and 1917 ran a serious risk of being gimmicky. But Mendes, working with master cinematographer Roger Deakins, uses the single-take concept to fully enhance the narrative.
critic.name: Chris Evangelista
publication.name: Slashfilm

quote: "1917" is a modern war classic and one of the best movies of the year.
critic.name: Johnny Oleksinski
publication.name: New York Post

quote: A visceral experience and visual masterclass, 1917 personalizes the immense scale of the only war to begin on horseback and end in the air.
critic.name: Rubin Safaya
publication.name: Cinemalogue

quote: 1917 is a visceral World War I movie that is both technically masterful and emotionally devastating. It's easily the best film of Mendes' career.
critic.name: James Mottram
publication.name: South China Morning Post

quote: An astonishing and remarkable cinematic achievement ... the epitome of widescreen filmmaking.
critic.name: Edward Douglas
publication.name: ComingSoon.net

quote: The artistry of how this movie is photographed will be marveled over for decades to come.
critic.name: Jason Guerrasio
publication.name: Business Insider

quote: 1917 is not only a technical feat, it's also an anxiety-inducing war thriller with digressions into horror and even French impressionism.
critic.name: Karl Delossantos
publication.name: Smash Cut Reviews

quote: Ultimately the story is pretty simple, and there are a couple of contrivances run into along the way, but 1917 primarily exists as a technical achievement, and in that capacity it is a true marvel.
critic.name: Eric Eisenberg
publication.name: CinemaBlend

quote: What Steven Spielberg has done with Saving Private Ryan and WWII films, Sam Mendes has done for WWI films.
critic.name: John Nguyen
publication.name: Nerd Reactor

quote: Yes, this is all filmed to look like one shot, but what is astonishing about Deakins and Mendes' framing is the often painterly way it walks through the valley of the shadow of death.
critic.name: David Crow
publication.name: Den of Geek

quote: A visual knockout, a gripping war drama, a relentless action picture, a great "video game movie not based on a video game" and an ironic inversion of the 'Lord of the Rings.'
critic.name: Scott Mendelson
publication.name: Forbes

quote: Let there be no doubt that everyone involved with 1917 gave their all to the exercise. But its ultimate status as an exercise is, likewise, without doubt.
critic.name: Robbie Collin
publication.name: Daily Telegraph (UK)

quote: What's meant to be an epic film has the emotional heft of David Copperfield making an airplane disappear.
critic.name: Matt Patches
publication.name: Polygon

quote: It may be a grandiose flourish, but you can't deny it makes for a startlingly literal theater of war.
critic.name: Justin Chang
publication.name: Los Angeles Times

quote: The movie is more successful as a thriller than as a thoughtful examination of war and its horrors; Mendes seems less interested in the nightmare of battle and its effects on his characters than he is in Hitchcockian audience manipulation.
critic.name: Alonso Duralde
publication.name: TheWrap

quote: There's an audacity here which is completely unexpected.
critic.name: Fionnuala Halligan
publication.name: Screen International

quote: This immersive, visceral experience transcends the continuous-shot concept to augment the narrative's unrelenting nature and the propulsive character-driven scenarios.
critic.name: Courtney Howard
publication.name: Fresh Fiction

quote: [L]egendary cinematographer Roger Deakins (No Country for Old Men, Fargo, Blade Runner 2049) effectively drops the viewer in the center of the story and compels them to stay there, fully immersed in every muddy step, hunger pang, and rifle click.
critic.name: Leah Greenblatt
publication.name: Entertainment Weekly

quote: Sam Mendes' stunning World War I odyssey 1917 takes us to hell and back
critic.name: Mike Ryan
publication.name: Uproxx

quote: There's no time to pause, even for great beauty, a lesson that even "1917" is often loathe to honor.
critic.name: Kate Erbland
publication.name: indieWire
